menu "breadboard: bb_sub_mqtt"

config BB_SUB_MQTT_AUTOREGISTER
    bool "Auto-register bb_sub_mqtt ingress adapter via bb_init (regular tier)"
    default y
    help
        When enabled, bb_sub_mqtt self-registers at the regular bb_init
        tier. On init it loads CONFIG_BB_SUB_MQTT_TOPICS (space/comma-
        separated filter list) plus any filters already added via
        bb_sub_mqtt_add_topic(), subscribes each via bb_mqtt_subscribe() on
        bb_mqtt_default(), and registers bb_sub_route (via
        bb_mqtt_on_message()) as the MQTT receive callback. No-ops (logs +
        returns BB_OK) when no default MQTT client is configured. Disable
        to call bb_sub_mqtt_init() manually.

config BB_SUB_MQTT_TOPICS
    string "Default MQTT topic filter(s) to subscribe (space/comma-separated)"
    default "metrics/+/meta"
    help
        Subscribed at boot via bb_mqtt_subscribe(), one call per filter.
        Combine with bb_sub_mqtt_add_topic() for filters that can't be
        expressed as a static Kconfig default.

config BB_SUB_MQTT_INGEST_SELF
    bool "Ingest this device's own published topics back through bb_sub"
    default n
    help
        By default (n) bb_sub_mqtt drops any inbound message whose 2nd
        '/'-delimited topic segment equals this device's own hostname
        (bb_nv_config_hostname()) — i.e. "<prefix>/<hostname>/<subtopic>",
        matching bb_pub's own topic shape. This prevents a device that both
        publishes AND subscribes to the same wildcard (e.g.
        "metrics/+/meta") from ingesting its own published data back into
        bb_cache. Enable (y) to opt out of self-exclusion. Runtime override:
        bb_sub_mqtt_set_ignore_self().

endmenu
